modules.description: Generates and processes OAuth 2.0 authorization URLs, extracting codes and tokens from redirect URIs. It handles both implicit and authorization code flows, using client IDs, secrets, and redirect URIs to manage authentication states. Supports scenarios like mobile app authentication and server-side token exchange after user approval.

Extracts day, month, year, hour, minute, second, and weekday from date values. Converts date values to string representations. Operates on internal date type and associated enumeration types for weekdays and months. Used to format date information for logging or user display.

Provides context-aware HTTP request execution and response handling, including methods like GET, POST, PUT, and PATCH with customizable headers, body, and chunked encoding. Operates on HTTP request and response types, body streams, and context objects to manage request lifecycle. Enables direct API calls, form submissions, and low-level request processing with explicit control over I/O and context.

Handles setting and managing metadata for photo objects, including date, coordinates, and structured data like lists and tuples. Operates on date references, coordinate pairs, and custom structured data types. Used to serialize and deserialize photo data using JSON, preserving complex information formats.

Handles metadata manipulation with precise control over date, float, and structured data fields. Works with custom `info` records and a variant type supporting floats, integers, strings, and nested lists. Serializes and deserializes data to and from JSON using defined encoding and decoding routines.

Handles conversion between a custom type and JSON representations using Yojson. Provides precise serialization and deserialization for structured data. Used to encode and decode internal state in network communication and persistent storage.

Generates and processes OAuth 2.0 authorization URLs, extracts codes and tokens from redirect URIs, and exchanges codes for tokens using client credentials. Works with strings for client IDs, secrets, codes, and tokens, and with URIs for redirect handling. Used to initiate user authentication flows, capture authorization codes from web redirects, and obtain access tokens for API interactions.

Provides functions for interacting with the Dropbox Remote API, including file uploads, downloads, and metadata retrieval. Operates on types such as access tokens, file paths, and binary data. Used to build applications that synchronize files with Dropbox in a non-blocking, asynchronous manner.

Converts date strings to and from a structured date type, extracting components like day, month, year, hour, minute, second, and weekday. Works with custom types for months and weekdays, ensuring type-safe date manipulation. Parses and formats dates for use in API interactions or log processing.

The module provides JSON encoding and decoding functions for Dropbox-specific data types, including user information, shared folders, metadata, and authentication tokens, with support for both string and buffer-based operations. It handles structured data for managing file systems, user permissions, and API interactions, enabling efficient serialization of complex objects like metadata lists and upload states. Specific use cases include processing API responses, handling file metadata, and managing shared content within Dropbox integrations.

Handles OAuth 2.0 authentication for API access by generating authorization URLs, parsing codes and tokens from redirect URIs, and exchanging codes for tokens using client credentials. Operates on strings for client IDs, secrets, codes, and tokens, and on URIs for redirect handling. Enables initiation of user authentication, capture of authorization codes, and acquisition of access tokens for API calls. Example tasks include constructing an authorization link, extracting a code from a redirect, and obtaining a token to authenticate API requests.

Manages complex photo metadata through serialization and deserialization of structured data, including dates, coordinates, and nested lists. Operates on custom records and variant types, supporting precise manipulation of float, integer, and string fields. Enables conversion between internal representations and JSON for storage and communication. Examples include storing geotagged photos with timestamps and retrieving nested metadata from JSON payloads.

This module defines structured data models for representing Dropbox entities such as files, users, shared folders, and permissions, along with API-specific types like link structures, cursor tracking, and error descriptions. It supports operations involving file metadata, JSON delta updates, copy references, and chunked upload tracking, enabling precise interaction with Dropbox's API workflows. Use cases include managing file synchronization, handling API responses, and implementing error-resistant data transfers.
